.SH NAME
Selection.modify \- Selection: modify() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Selection.modify()\f[B]\f[R] method applies a change to
the current selection or cursor position, using simple textual commands.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
modify(alter, direction, granularity)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]alter\f[R]
The type of change to apply.
Specify \f[CR]\(dqmove\(dq\f[R] to move the current cursor position or
\f[CR]\(dqextend\(dq\f[R] to extend the current selection.
.TP
\f[B]direction\f[R]
The direction in which to adjust the current selection.
You can specify \f[CR]\(dqforward\(dq\f[R] or
\f[CR]\(dqbackward\(dq\f[R] to adjust in the appropriate direction based
on the language at the selection point.
If you want to adjust in a specific direction, you can specify
\f[CR]\(dqleft\(dq\f[R] or \f[CR]\(dqright\(dq\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]granularity\f[R]
The distance to adjust the current selection or cursor position.
You can move by \f[CR]\(dqcharacter\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqword\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqsentence\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqline\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqparagraph\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqlineboundary\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqsentenceboundary\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqparagraphboundary\(dq\f[R], or
\f[CR]\(dqdocumentboundary\(dq\f[R].
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Firefox does \f[B]not\f[R] implement
\f[CR]\(dqsentence\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqparagraph\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqsentenceboundary\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqparagraphboundary\(dq\f[R], or
\f[CR]\(dqdocumentboundary\(dq\f[R].
WebKit and Blink do.
.RE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Starting in Firefox 5, the \f[CR]\(dqword\(dq\f[R]
granularity no longer includes the following space, regardless of the
default platform behavior.
This makes the behavior more consistent, as well as making it work the
same way WebKit used to work, but unfortunately they have recently
changed their behavior.
.RE
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
